Micrometer doesn&#39;t provide a direct API for updating the value of a gauge with dynamically retrieved labels, so your approaches are reasonable workarounds. However, your second approach using a `ConcurrentHashMap` to hold references to the gauges can be improved for clarity and safety. Here&#39;s an updated version of your second approach:

```java
private final ConcurrentMap&lt;Tags, AtomicLong&gt; cycleGaugeMap = new ConcurrentHashMap&lt;&gt;();

private void updateGauge(String currency, int minutes) {
    Tags tags = Tags.of(&quot;currency&quot;, currency);
    AtomicLong gaugeValue = cycleGaugeMap.computeIfAbsent(tags, key -&gt; {
        AtomicLong gauge = new AtomicLong(minutes);
        meterRegistry.gauge(&quot;withdraw.cycle&quot;, tags, gauge);
        return gauge;
    });

    gaugeValue.set(minutes);
}
```

In this updated version, `computeIfAbsent` is used to atomically check if the gauge already exists in the `cycleGaugeMap`. If it doesn&#39;t exist, it creates the gauge and registers it with Micrometer before returning the reference to it. This ensures that gauge creation and retrieval are done atomically and avoids the need to separately check and putIfAbsent.

This approach is more concise and still thread-safe. It also clearly conveys your intention of creating and managing gauges dynamically while keeping track of them for future updates.

Overall, this updated version of your second approach is a reasonable and elegant way to manage dynamically labeled gauges in Micrometer.

