There is some lack of clarity in the instructions your professor gave. The instructions are open to interpretation. It may be the professor relied on students&#39; understanding of material presented in the lecture or previous assignments. However, we on Stack Overflow don&#39;t have access to that unless you update the question. It may be the students need to discuss this with the professor and request explanations. Presenting examples would be a good idea.

Nonetheless, I have some suggestions:

**First** *&quot;Each transaction takes a random amount of time to complete.&quot;*

I assume a transaction is a customer checking out. One way to handle this is to &quot;glue&quot; transaction time to a customer. Fields can be &quot;glued&quot; together through instances of a `class`. So, a `Customer` class may be appropriate:

     public class Customer {
       public static int nextID = 0;
       private final int customerID;
       private int transactionTime;  // remaining, countdown 
    
       public Customer () { 
           customerID = ++nextID;
           transactionTime = 10;
       }
    
       public Customer (int time) { 
          customerID = ++nextID;
          transactionTime = time;
       }
    
       public int getID () { return customerID; }
       public int tick () { return --transactionTime; }  
       @Override
       public String toString () { return &quot;Customer &quot; + customerID + &quot; &quot;; }
    }

The constructor assigns customer numbers in order. I do not believe having the customer numbers in random order is a requirement. 

The transaction time is number of clock ticks to complete a transaction.  

**Next**, I would like to mention an issue with arrays and generics. Because of the way generics were implemented in Java, arrays and generics do not work well together. You should not create an array of a generic `Collection`. A line such as the following will generate an &quot;generic array creation&quot; compiler error: 

    Queue&lt;Integer&gt;[] checkoutLines = new Queue&lt;Integer&gt;[numCheckoutLines];

To get around that, you can nest generics. In the suggested code in this answer, I used this line:
          
    List&lt;Queue&lt;Customer&gt;&gt; checkoutLines = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(NUM_CHECKOUT_LINES);

If you want to access a specific checkout queue, use code like the following:

     Queue&lt;Customer&gt; lane = checkoutLines.get(3);

This accesses lane 3. Of course, you would replace `3` with a variable or expression that resolves to an integer.

The code for `findShortestLine` and `allQueuesEmpty` looks like this:

    // Find the shortest checkout lane
    private static int findShortestLine(List&lt;Queue&lt;Customer&gt;&gt; checkoutLines) {
        int shortestLineIndex = 0;
        int minLength = checkoutLines.size();

        for (int i = 1; i &lt; checkoutLines.size(); i++) {
            int length = checkoutLines.get(i).size();
            if (length &lt; minLength) {
                minLength = length;
                shortestLineIndex = i;
            }
        }
        return shortestLineIndex;
    }

    // Check if all checkout lines are empty
    private static boolean allQueuesEmpty(List&lt;Queue&lt;Customer&gt;&gt; checkoutLines) {
        for (Queue&lt;Customer&gt; line : checkoutLines) {
            if (!line.isEmpty()) {
                return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }

**By the way**, Named constants are usually declared with `final`, and with names written in all uppercase.  The beginning of the program looks like this:

        public class GroceryStore {

           public static void main(String[] args) {

              final int    NUM_CHECKOUT_LINES = 5;
              final double PROBABILITY_CUSTOMER_JOINS = 0.35;
              final int    MAX_TRANSACTION_TIME = 25;
              final int    MAX_CUSTOMERS = 40;    

              List&lt;Queue&lt;Customer&gt;&gt; checkoutLines
                   = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(NUM_CHECKOUT_LINES);
              Random random = new Random(); 

 - `NUM_CHECKOUT_LINES` is your `numCheckoutLines`
 - `MAX_CUSTOMERS` is the maximum number of customers that will be processed in one run of the simulation. It corresponds to your 
 - `numCustomers`, but is not quite the same. 
 - `MAX_TRANSACTION_TIME` is the maximum amount of time (ticks) a customer will take to check out.
 - `PROBABILITY_CUSTOMER_JOINS` is the probability that one customer will begin waiting in line in one tick. 

**Trivial** Since you are to &quot;Open&quot; the store with one customer in each lane, you can create the lanes and first customers at the same time. 

        // Initialize checkout lines
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; NUM_CHECKOUT_LINES; i++) {
